Introduction: From Python to Physical Computing

Welcome to Hardware Programming!

You have spent Week 5 mastering Python fundamentalsvariables, loops, functions, and data structures. Now comes the exciting part: using Python to control physical hardware on your Raspberry Pi. This is where your software skills meet the real world.

By now, you are already familiar with the Raspberry Pi from previous work in this course. You know how to navigate Raspberry Pi OS, use the terminal, and run Python programs. This week builds on that experience, teaching you to interact with the physical pins and sensors.

Raspberry Pi 4 Model B showing 40-pin GPIO header

What Makes Raspberry Pi Special for Physical Computing?

Unlike a regular computer, your Raspberry Pi has 40 physical pins along its edge called GPIO (General Purpose Input/Output) pins. These pins allow your Python programs to interact with the physical worldturning LEDs on and off, reading button presses, controlling motors, and reading sensors. Think of GPIO pins as the bridge between your code and real-world electronics.

Python comes pre-installed on Raspberry Pi OS with powerful hardware libraries already available. This means you can write a program and immediately see physical resultsno compilation, no waiting. You will use three main libraries: RPi.GPIO for low-level control, gpiozero for simpler high-level operations, and sense_hat for the Sense HAT accessory.

Introducing the Sense HAT

The Raspberry Pi Sense HAT is an add-on board that sits on top of your Raspberry Pi, connecting to the GPIO header. Originally designed for the Astro Pi program on the International Space Station, it provides a complete physical computing platform in one compact package.

The Sense HAT includes: - 88 RGB LED Matrix - 64 full-color LEDs - Environmental Sensors - Temperature, humidity, pressure - Motion Sensors - Accelerometer, gyroscope, magnetometer - 5-Button Joystick - For interactive input

Raspberry Pi Sense HAT with 88 LED matrix

Part 2 - Sense HAT Programming: You will explore the Sense HAT hardware, learn to program its 88 LED matrix, and read environmental sensors. After these reading sections, you will complete a comprehensive Sense HAT exercise.

Part 3 - Conclusion: Summary and resources for continued learning.

Important Notes: - Device Drivers: We are using Python libraries that handle device driver interactions for us. The underlying driver concepts and file system details will be covered in upcoming lectures. - Physical Hardware vs Emulator: The same Python code works on both physical Sense HAT hardware and the emulatoronly the import statement changes! - Your Experience: You already know how to work with Raspberry Pi from earlier in the course. Today builds on that foundation.

Let us begin by understanding the GPIO pins that make all of this possible!

Choosing the Right Library for the Job

Before you start controlling hardware, you need to understand the tools available to you. Raspberry Pi offers three main Python libraries for hardware programming, each with different strengths. Throughout this course, youll use all three, so lets explore when and why youd choose each one.

RPi.GPIO: The Traditional Approach

RPi.GPIO is the original, industry-standard library for Raspberry Pi hardware control. It gives you precise, low-level control over GPIO pins. When you use RPi.GPIO, youre writing code thats very explicit about whats happening at the hardware level.

Heres a typical RPi.GPIO program:

import RPi.GPIO as GPIO

GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BCM)          # Choose pin numbering system
GPIO.setup(17, GPIO.OUT)        # Configure pin 17 as output
GPIO.output(17, GPIO.HIGH)      # Turn the pin on (3.3V)

Notice how you must explicitly set the mode, configure each pin, and control the output state. This requires more code, but gives you fine-grained control. Youll use RPi.GPIO when you need precise timing or when working with hardware that requires specific pin configurations.

gpiozero: The Beginner-Friendly Alternative

The gpiozero library was designed to make hardware programming more intuitive and Pythonic. Instead of thinking about pins and voltage levels, you think about devicesLEDs, buttons, motors. The same LED control becomes much simpler:

from gpiozero import LED

led = LED(17)                   # Create an LED object on pin 17
led.on()                        # Turn it on!

Thats itjust two lines! The library handles all the setup and configuration behind the scenes. Youll start with gpiozero because it lets you focus on learning concepts rather than syntax. It includes built-in classes for common components like LEDs, buttons, motors, and sensors.

sense_hat: Purpose-Built for the SenseHat

The SenseHat is a special add-on board with an 88 LED matrix and multiple sensors. It requires its own specialized library:

from sense_hat import SenseHat

sense = SenseHat()
sense.show_message("Hello!")

Youll use this library exclusively in Session 2 when working with the SenseHat hardware and emulator.

Your Strategy for This Course

In Session 1, youll primarily use gpiozero for its simplicity and clarity. Youll also see RPi.GPIO examples to understand how low-level control works. In Session 2, youll switch to sense_hat for all SenseHat-related work. This progression helps you understand both high-level and low-level approaches to hardware programming.

Exploring the GPIO Pins on Your Raspberry Pi

Finding the GPIO Header

Look at your Raspberry Pi board. Along one edge, youll see two rows of metal pins40 pins in total, arranged in 20 pairs. This is called the GPIO header, and its your gateway to physical computing. GPIO stands for General Purpose Input/Output, which means these pins can be programmed to do many different things.

Take a moment to examine these pins carefully. Some are for power (providing 3.3V or 5V to your circuits), some are ground connections (completing the electrical circuit), and many are GPIO pins you can control with Python code. Dont worry about memorizing which is which yetwell explore that next.

What Can GPIO Pins Do?

Each GPIO pin can be configured in your Python code as either an INPUT or an OUTPUT:

  • OUTPUT mode: Your program sends electrical signals OUT through the pin. This is how you turn an LED on (send 3.3V) or off (send 0V). Think of it as your Raspberry Pi talking to the outside world.

  • INPUT mode: Your program reads electrical signals coming IN through the pin. This is how you detect button presses or read sensor data. Think of it as your Raspberry Pi listening to the outside world.

Today, youll focus on OUTPUT mode to control an LED. In future projects, you might use INPUT mode to read buttons, sensors, or other input devices.

Understanding the 40-Pin Layout

Of the 40 pins on your Raspberry Pi 4, not all are GPIO pins: - 26 pins are programmable GPIO pins you can use in your code - 8 pins provide power (two 3.3V pins, two 5V pins, and four ground pins) - 6 pins are special-purpose communication pins (I2C, SPI, UART) for advanced projects

For this session, youll use just one GPIO pin (GPIO17) and one ground pin. Thats all you need to make an LED blink!

Important: GPIO17 is already connected to an LED on your Raspberry Pi board through a relay circuit. This means you dont need to build any external circuitthe LED is built into the board and ready to use. When you control GPIO17 in your code, youre actually controlling this onboard LED.

The Two Numbering Systems: A Common Source of Confusion

Heres something important: there are two different ways to refer to the same physical pin, and this confuses many beginners. Lets clarify this now:

  • BCM numbering (Broadcom Chip Mode): BCM stands for Broadcom, the company that manufactures the processor chip inside your Raspberry Pi. This numbering system uses the GPIO numbers directly assigned by the Broadcom BCM2835/BCM2711 chip. For example, GPIO17 or GPIO27. These numbers correspond to the actual pin numbers on the Broadcom processor, not the physical header position. This is what most documentation uses.

  • BOARD numbering (Physical pin position): Uses the physical position on the header. For example, Pin 11 or Pin 13.

The same physical pin can be called GPIO17 (BCM) or Pin 11 (BOARD). Theyre two names for the same thing!

Which Should You Use?

Well use BCM numbering throughout this course because: - Most online tutorials and documentation use BCM - The Raspberry Pi pinout diagrams show GPIO numbers - It matches the official Raspberry Pi naming convention

When you see GPIO17 in our code, youre referring to a specific pin by its BCM number, not its physical position.

Activity: Locating Your Pins and Understanding Pin Numbering

Step 1: Understanding Pin Numbering in Code

Before connecting any hardware, lets see how pin numbering works in Python. The first line of any GPIO program must tell Python which numbering system youre using.

Heres how you set BCM mode (which well use):

import RPi.GPIO as GPIO

GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BCM)           # Use BCM numbering
GPIO.setup(17, GPIO.OUT)         # Configure GPIO17 as output

In this code, GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BCM) tells Python: When I say 17, I mean GPIO17 (the BCM number), not physical pin position 17.

If you used BOARD mode instead, the same physical pin would be referenced differently:

GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BOARD)         # Use physical pin numbers
GPIO.setup(11, GPIO.OUT)         # Physical pin 11 (same pin as GPIO17!)

Both code snippets control the exact same physical pinthey just call it by different names. Stick with BCM mode to avoid confusion.

Step 2: Using the GPIO Pinout Diagram

Lets identify the specific pins youll use for your first LED project. Heres a simplified pinout diagram showing the key pins:

Raspberry Pi 4 GPIO Pinout (40-pin header):

3.3V  [ 1] [ 2]  5V
GPIO2 [ 3] [ 4]  5V
GPIO3 [ 5] [ 6]  GND     <-- Ground (we'll use this)
GPIO4 [ 7] [ 8]  GPIO14
GND   [ 9] [10]  GPIO15
GPIO17[11] [12]  GPIO18  <-- GPIO17 (we'll use this for LED!)
GPIO27[13] [14]  GND
GPIO22[15] [16]  GPIO23
3.3V  [17] [18]  GPIO24
GPIO10[19] [20]  GND
GPIO9 [21] [22]  GPIO25
GPIO11[23] [24]  GPIO8
GND   [25] [26]  GPIO7
...and more

Your Task: Locate these two pins on your Raspberry Pi: 1. GPIO17 - This is physical pin 11 (6th pin down on the left column) 2. GND - Any ground pin works; pin 6 is convenient (3rd pin down on the right column)

Step 3: Explore the Full Pinout

For complete pinout details with color-coded diagrams, open a web browser on your Raspberry Pi and visit:

https://pinout.xyz

This interactive website shows every pin with its function, GPIO number, and physical position. Bookmark this pageyoull refer to it often!

Common GPIO Pins Youll Use in Projects:

As you progress through this course, youll encounter these pins frequently: - GPIO17 (Physical pin 11): Your first LED today - GPIO27 (Physical pin 13): Often used for a second LED or button - GPIO22 (Physical pin 15): Third component in multi-part projects - GND pins: Available at pins 6, 9, 14, 20, 25, 30, 34, and 39

Critical Safety Reminders Before You Begin:

IMPORTANT - Voltage Warning: Raspberry Pi uses 3.3V logic, not 5V like Arduino. Applying 5V to a GPIO pin can permanently damage your Pi!

IMPORTANT - LED Resistors: ALWAYS use a current-limiting resistor (typically 220 to 330) with LEDs. Without a resistor, you risk damaging the GPIO pin.

IMPORTANT - No Short Circuits: Never connect power directly to ground. This can damage your Pi or power supply. Double-check all connections before powering on.

IMPORTANT - Current Limits: Each GPIO pin can safely provide up to 16mA. All pins combined shouldnt exceed 50mA. For higher current devices (motors, etc.), use external power with transistors or relays.

Now that you understand pin numbering and safety, youre ready to build your first circuit!

Lab Activity: Your First Hardware Program - Blinking an LED

What Youll Learn

In this hands-on activity, youll write Python code to control the onboard LED connected to GPIO17 on your Raspberry Pi. This simple project teaches fundamental concepts youll use in every hardware program: GPIO configuration, output control, and proper cleanup.

What You Need: - Your Raspberry Pi with onboard LED connected to GPIO17 - No external components requiredthe LED is already wired on the board!

Writing Your First GPIO Program

Your Raspberry Pi has an LED already connected to GPIO17 through a built-in relay circuit. This means you can start programming immediately without building any circuits. Lets write code to control it!

Open Thonny IDE and create a new file called blink_led.py. Type the following code, reading the comments to understand each line:

import RPi.GPIO as GPIO
import time

# Setup: Tell Python how we're numbering pins
GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BCM)

# Configure GPIO17 as an output pin
GPIO.setup(17, GPIO.OUT)

try:
    # Main loop: runs forever until you press Ctrl+C
    while True:
        GPIO.output(17, GPIO.HIGH)  # Turn LED on (send 3.3V)
        print("LED ON")
        time.sleep(1)                # Wait 1 second
        
        GPIO.output(17, GPIO.LOW)   # Turn LED off (send 0V)
        print("LED OFF")
        time.sleep(1)                # Wait 1 second
        
finally:
    # Cleanup: Release the GPIO resources
    GPIO.cleanup()
    print("GPIO cleaned up")

Understanding the Code:

  • GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BCM): Tells Python were using BCM pin numbering
  • GPIO.setup(17, GPIO.OUT): Configures GPIO17 as an output (well send signals out)
  • GPIO.output(17, GPIO.HIGH): Sends 3.3V to the pin (LED turns on)
  • GPIO.output(17, GPIO.LOW): Sends 0V to the pin (LED turns off)
  • time.sleep(1): Pauses for 1 second
  • try/finally: Ensures cleanup happens even if you interrupt the program
  • GPIO.cleanup(): Releases GPIO resources (prevents errors in future programs)

Run Your Program:

  1. Save the file
  2. In the terminal, run: sudo python3 blink_led.py
  3. Watch the onboard LED blink on and off every second!
  4. Press Ctrl+C to stop the program

Experiment and Explore:

Now that your LED is blinking, try modifying the code:

  1. Change the speed: Try time.sleep(0.1) for faster blinking or time.sleep(2) for slower
  2. Create patterns: Make the LED blink 3 times quickly, then pause for 2 seconds
  3. Morse code: Create an SOS signal ( )

Troubleshooting:

  • LED doesnt light: Verify GPIO17 is the correct pin on your board, check that the code is running
  • Permission denied error: Run with sudo python3 filename.py
  • Channel already in use: Previous program didnt cleanup. Run sudo python3 -c "import RPi.GPIO as GPIO; GPIO.cleanup()"

Congratulations! Youve just written your first hardware control program. The concepts youve learnedsetting up GPIO pins, controlling output, and cleanupform the foundation of all hardware programming projects.

Essential Practices: GPIO Cleanup and Hardware Safety

Why GPIO Cleanup Matters

Youve successfully made an LED blinkexcellent work! But before moving on, lets discuss a critical concept that prevents frustrating errors in future programs: GPIO cleanup.

When your Python program configures a GPIO pin (with GPIO.setup()), it claims exclusive control of that pin. If your program ends without properly releasing that pin, the next program you run will fail with a Channel already in use error. This is especially common when you interrupt a program with Ctrl+C.

The Solution: Always Clean Up

Every GPIO program should release its pins when finished. Heres how to do it properly:

Method 1: Using try/finally with RPi.GPIO

The finally block ensures cleanup happens even if your program crashes or is interrupted:

import RPi.GPIO as GPIO

try:
    GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BCM)
    GPIO.setup(17, GPIO.OUT)
    # Your program code here...
    
except KeyboardInterrupt:
    print("\nProgram interrupted by user")
    
finally:
    GPIO.cleanup()  # This ALWAYS runs, no matter what!
    print("GPIO pins released successfully")

When you press Ctrl+C, the program will: 1. Catch the interrupt in the except block 2. Print Program interrupted by user 3. Jump to the finally block 4. Run GPIO.cleanup() to release all pins 5. Exit cleanly

Method 2: Using gpiozero (Automatic Cleanup)

One advantage of gpiozero is that it handles cleanup automatically when your program ends:

from gpiozero import LED

led = LED(17)
# Use the LED...
# When program ends, gpiozero automatically releases the pin!

However, its still good practice to explicitly close devices:

from gpiozero import LED

try:
    led = LED(17)
    # Use the LED...
finally:
    led.close()  # Explicitly release the pin
    print("LED resources released")

Emergency Cleanup

If you forgot to cleanup and now cant run a new program, use this one-line fix in the terminal:

sudo python3 -c "import RPi.GPIO as GPIO; GPIO.cleanup()"

This runs a quick Python command that cleans up all GPIO pins.

Hardware Safety Guidelines: Protecting Your Raspberry Pi

Now lets talk about hardware safety. Unlike Arduino, Raspberry Pi GPIO pins are fragile and directly connected to the main processor. Mistakes can permanently damage your Pi. Follow these rules carefully:

Rule 1: Never Exceed 3.3V on GPIO Pins

Raspberry Pi uses 3.3V logic, unlike Arduinos 5V. Connecting 5V to a GPIO pin will likely destroy it. - Correct: Use 3.3V sensors and components - Wrong: Connecting Arduino (5V) sensors directly - Solution: Use a level shifter for 5V devices

Rule 2: Always Use Resistors with LEDs

LEDs have very low resistance. Without a resistor, theyll draw too much current and damage the GPIO pin. - Correct: LED 220 resistor GPIO pin - Wrong: LED connected directly to GPIO pin - Resistor values: 220 to 330 work well for standard LEDs

Rule 3: Prevent Short Circuits

Connecting power directly to ground creates a short circuit, potentially damaging your Pi or power supply. - Correct: Always have a component (LED + resistor, motor, etc.) between power and ground - Wrong: Wire directly from 3.3V or 5V to GND - Best practice: Double-check all connections before powering on

Rule 4: Respect Current Limits

Each GPIO pin can safely provide 16mA maximum. All pins combined shouldnt exceed 50mA. - Correct: Single LED with resistor (draws ~10mA) - Wrong: Multiple high-power LEDs or motors directly from GPIO - For motors: Use external power supply with transistor or relay

Rule 5: Use External Power for Motors and Servos

Motors and servos draw too much current for GPIO pins to handle directly. - Correct: Separate 5V/12V power supply + transistor/relay for control - Wrong: Powering motors from 5V or 3.3V pins - Control method: Use GPIO to trigger a transistor that switches motor power

Common Problems and Solutions

Problem: LED doesnt light up at all
Solution: Check LED polarity (long leg toward GPIO17), verify resistor is connected, confirm code is running

Problem: Channel already in use error
Solution: Run GPIO.cleanup() or restart Python. Add try/finally blocks to prevent this

Problem: Permission denied when running code
Solution: GPIO requires root access. Run with sudo python3 your_script.py

Problem: No module named RPi error
Solution: Install the library: sudo apt install python3-rpi.gpio

Activity: Practice Safe Cleanup

Try this experiment to understand cleanup:

  1. Run your LED blink program
  2. Press Ctrl+C to interrupt it
  3. Run the program again immediately
  4. If you get Channel already in use, your cleanup didnt work
  5. Add a try/finally block and test again

With proper cleanup and safety practices, youll avoid 90% of common hardware programming problems!

EXERCISE 1: LED Control and Patterns (15 minutes)

Objective: Apply your GPIO knowledge to control an LED on GPIO17, creating different blinking patterns and practicing proper cleanup procedures.

What You Will Build:

In this hands-on exercise, you will: 1. Write a program to blink the LED on GPIO17 2. Create custom blinking patterns 3. Practice proper GPIO cleanup

Note: This exercise assumes the LED hardware is already connected to GPIO17.

Step 1: Write Your First LED Program (10 minutes)

2.1 Create the Program File

Open Thonny IDE and create a new file. Save it as led_blink_exercise.py in your home directory.

1.2 Write the Basic Blinking Code

Type the following code carefully, reading the comments:

#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
GPIO Exercise 1: LED Blinking
Control an LED on GPIO17
"""

import RPi.GPIO as GPIO
from time import sleep

# Setup GPIO mode
GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BCM)
GPIO.setwarnings(False)

# Configure GPIO17 as output
GPIO.setup(17, GPIO.OUT)

print("Starting LED blink program...")
print("Press Ctrl+C to stop")

try:
    # Main loop - blink forever
    while True:
        GPIO.output(17, GPIO.HIGH)  # Turn LED on
        print("LED ON")
        sleep(1)                     # Wait 1 second
        
        GPIO.output(17, GPIO.LOW)   # Turn LED off
        print("LED OFF")
        sleep(1)                     # Wait 1 second

except KeyboardInterrupt:
    # User pressed Ctrl+C
    print("\nProgram stopped by user")

finally:
    # Clean up GPIO resources
    GPIO.cleanup()
    print("GPIO cleaned up successfully")

1.3 Run Your Program

In the terminal, navigate to where you saved the file and run:

python3 led_blink_exercise.py

Expected Result: - Your LED should blink on and off every second - The terminal should print LED ON and LED OFF - Press Ctrl+C to stop

Troubleshooting:

Problem Solution
Permission denied error Run with sudo python3 led_blink_exercise.py
Channel already in use error Run cleanup: sudo python3 -c "import RPi.GPIO as GPIO; GPIO.cleanup()"
Program wont stop with Ctrl+C Check that try/except KeyboardInterrupt is in your code

Step 2: Create Custom Blinking Patterns (5 minutes)

3.1 Fast Blink Pattern

Modify your code to make the LED blink faster. Change the sleep() values:

try:
    while True:
        led.on()
        sleep(0.2)      # 0.2 seconds = faster blink
        led.off()
        sleep(0.2)

Expected Result: LED blinks 5 times per second (much faster!)

2.2 SOS Morse Code Pattern

Create an SOS distress signal pattern: ... --- ... (3 short, 3 long, 3 short)

Replace your while True loop with this:

def short_blink():
    """Short blink for morse code dot (.)"""
    GPIO.output(17, GPIO.HIGH)
    sleep(0.2)
    GPIO.output(17, GPIO.LOW)
    sleep(0.2)

def long_blink():
    """Long blink for morse code dash (-)"""
    GPIO.output(17, GPIO.HIGH)
    sleep(0.6)
    GPIO.output(17, GPIO.LOW)
    sleep(0.2)

try:
    while True:
        # S: dot dot dot
        print("S")
        short_blink()
        short_blink()
        short_blink()
        sleep(0.4)  # Pause between letters
        
        # O: dash dash dash
        print("O")
        long_blink()
        long_blink()
        long_blink()
        sleep(0.4)
        
        # S: dot dot dot
        print("S")
        short_blink()
        short_blink()
        short_blink()
        sleep(2)    # Pause before repeating

Expected Result: LED blinks ... --- ... pattern continuously (SOS in Morse code!)

2.3 Traffic Light Simulator (Challenge)

Create a traffic light sequence: Red (3s) Yellow (1s) Green (3s) Yellow (1s) repeat

Hint: Use the LED color to represent different states: - LED ON for 3 seconds = Red light - LED fast blink (0.5s) = Yellow light
- LED OFF for 3 seconds = Green light

Try writing this yourself before looking at the solution below!

Click to see solution 
try:
    while True:
        # Red light - LED ON
        print("RED - Stop!")
        GPIO.output(17, GPIO.HIGH)
        sleep(3)
        
        # Yellow light - LED fast blink
        print("YELLOW - Get ready...")
        for _ in range(2):  # Blink twice
            GPIO.output(17, GPIO.LOW)
            sleep(0.25)
            GPIO.output(17, GPIO.HIGH)
            sleep(0.25)
        
        # Green light - LED OFF
        print("GREEN - Go!")
        GPIO.output(17, GPIO.LOW)
        sleep(3)
        
        # Yellow light again
        print("YELLOW - Slow down...")
        for _ in range(2):
            GPIO.output(17, GPIO.LOW)
            sleep(0.25)
            GPIO.output(17, GPIO.HIGH)
            sleep(0.25)

Introduction to Sense HAT Programming

Welcome to Session 2!

In Session 1, you learned the fundamentals of GPIO programming by making an LED blink. You built circuits, wrote code to control hardware, and practiced safety guidelines. Now its time to explore something more sophisticated: the Raspberry Pi SenseHat.

The SenseHat is an add-on board that sits on top of your Raspberry Pi, providing an 88 LED matrix display and multiple environmental sensors. Originally designed for the Astro Pi missions on the International Space Station, the SenseHat offers a complete physical computing platform in one compact package.

Your Learning Goals for Session 2: - Set up and test the SenseHat emulator - Program the 88 LED matrix to display messages and patterns - Read environmental sensor data (temperature, humidity, pressure) - Create interactive programs that combine sensors and display - Build practical applications using the SenseHat

Whether you have physical SenseHat hardware or are using the emulator, youll write the same Python code and see the same results. Lets begin!

Using Sense Hat Emulator: Quick Test

Testing Your Emulator Installation

Before diving into complex projects, lets verify that your SenseHat emulator is working correctly. This test script checks all major components: the LED display and the temperature sensor.

Create a new file called test_sense_hat.py:

#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
test_sense_hat.py
Test if Sense Hat Emulator is working
"""

from sense_emu import SenseHat
import time

def main():
    """Test Sense Hat emulator functionality"""
    sense = SenseHat()
    
    # Test 1: Display message
    print("Test 1: Displaying message...")
    sense.show_message("Hello CT101!", scroll_speed=0.05)
    
    # Test 2: Read temperature
    print("Test 2: Reading sensors...")
    temp = sense.get_temperature()
    print(f"Temperature: {temp:.1f}C")
    
    # Test 3: Light up LEDs
    print("Test 3: Testing LED matrix...")
    sense.clear([255, 0, 0])  # Red
    time.sleep(1)
    sense.clear([0, 255, 0])  # Green
    time.sleep(1)
    sense.clear([0, 0, 255])  # Blue
    time.sleep(1)
    sense.clear()
    
    print("All tests completed!")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()

Run the test:

python3 test_sense_hat.py

You should see: 1. Hello CT101! scroll across the 88 LED matrix 2. A temperature reading printed to the console 3. The LED matrix flash red, green, then blue before clearing

Switching Between Hardware and Emulator

The beauty of the SenseHat library is that the same code works on both real hardware and the emulator. You just change one line:

# For emulator:
from sense_emu import SenseHat

# For real hardware:
from sense_hat import SenseHat

Everything else in your code remains identical!

Introducing the SenseHat Hardware

What is the SenseHat?

The Raspberry Pi SenseHat is an add-on board that connects to your Raspberry Pis 40-pin GPIO header. It was specifically designed for the Astro Pi program, where British ESA astronaut Tim Peake used two Raspberry Pi computers equipped with SenseHats aboard the International Space Station during his mission in 2015-2016.

Hardware Features:

The SenseHat packs remarkable capabilities into a small board:

  • 88 RGB LED Matrix: 64 individually controllable full-color LEDs for visual output
  • Temperature Sensor: Measures ambient temperature (with some caveats well discuss)
  • Humidity Sensor: Measures relative humidity as a percentage
  • Pressure Sensor: Measures atmospheric pressure in millibars
  • Accelerometer: Detects acceleration and orientation in 3D space
  • Gyroscope: Measures rotational movement
  • Magnetometer: Acts as a digital compass, detecting magnetic fields
  • 5-Button Joystick: Provides directional input (up, down, left, right, push)

Why the SenseHat is Perfect for Teaching:

Rather than connecting individual sensors and displays with jumper wires, the SenseHat gives you a complete physical computing platform in one package. This lets you focus on programming concepts rather than circuit building. The combination of input (sensors, joystick), processing (Raspberry Pi), and output (LED matrix) makes it ideal for learning computational thinking and data visualization.

SenseHat vs SenseHat Emulator:

  • Physical SenseHat: Real hardware that connects to your Pi. Provides actual sensor readings from the environment.
  • SenseHat Emulator: Software simulation that runs on any computer. Lets you control sensor values manually for testing.

The Python code is identical for bothonly the import statement changes!

SenseHat LED Matrix Programming

Understanding the 88 LED Matrix

The SenseHats LED matrix consists of 64 RGB LEDs arranged in an 88 grid. Each LED can display any color by mixing red, green, and blue values from 0 to 255, giving you 16.7 million possible colors!

Basic Display Methods:

from sense_hat import SenseHat

sense = SenseHat()

# Display a scrolling message
sense.show_message("Hello CT101!")

# Display a single letter (fills the 8x8 grid)
sense.show_letter("G", text_colour=[0, 255, 0])  # Green G

# Set individual pixels at coordinates (x, y) with RGB color
sense.set_pixel(0, 0, 255, 0, 0)  # Red pixel at top-left
sense.set_pixel(7, 7, 0, 0, 255)  # Blue pixel at bottom-right

# Clear the display (turn all LEDs off)
sense.clear()

# Fill entire display with one color
sense.clear([255, 0, 0])  # Red background

Understanding Coordinates:

The LED matrix uses a coordinate system: - (0, 0) is the top-left corner - (7, 7) is the bottom-right corner - X increases going right (0 to 7) - Y increases going down (0 to 7)

Creating Complex Patterns with set_pixels():

For custom images, you can define all 64 pixels at once:

from sense_hat import SenseHat

sense = SenseHat()

# Define colors
R = [255, 0, 0]    # Red
G = [0, 255, 0]    # Green
B = [0, 0, 255]    # Blue
O = [0, 0, 0]      # Off/Black

# Create a simple cross pattern (8 rows  8 columns = 64 pixels)
# Read left-to-right, top-to-bottom
cross = [
    O, O, O, R, R, O, O, O,
    O, O, O, R, R, O, O, O,
    O, O, O, R, R, O, O, O,
    R, R, R, R, R, R, R, R,
    R, R, R, R, R, R, R, R,
    O, O, O, R, R, O, O, O,
    O, O, O, R, R, O, O, O,
    O, O, O, R, R, O, O, O
]

sense.set_pixels(cross)

Reading SenseHat Sensors

Environmental Sensors

The SenseHat includes three environmental sensors that measure conditions around your Raspberry Pi:

from sense_hat import SenseHat

sense = SenseHat()

# Get sensor readings
temp = sense.get_temperature()      # Celsius
pressure = sense.get_pressure()     # Millibars (hPa)
humidity = sense.get_humidity()     # Percentage

# Display the readings
print(f"Temperature: {temp:.1f}C")
print(f"Pressure: {pressure:.1f} mb")
print(f"Humidity: {humidity:.1f}%")

Example Output:

Temperature: 23.5C
Pressure: 1013.2 mb
Humidity: 45.3%

Important Note About Temperature:

The SenseHat temperature sensor tends to read higher than actual room temperature because its affected by heat from the Raspberry Pi processor. For accurate room temperature, you may need to apply a correction factor or use an external sensor. For learning purposes, the readings are still useful for observing changes.

Orientation Sensors (Accelerometer & Gyroscope):

The SenseHat can detect its orientation in 3D space:

# Get orientation as pitch, roll, yaw angles
orientation = sense.get_orientation()
pitch = orientation['pitch']  # Rotation around X-axis
roll = orientation['roll']    # Rotation around Y-axis
yaw = orientation['yaw']      # Rotation around Z-axis

print(f"Pitch: {pitch:.1f}")
print(f"Roll: {roll:.1f}")
print(f"Yaw: {yaw:.1f}")

These values change as you tilt the Raspberry Pi in different directions. Pitch, roll, and yaw are the three axes of rotation used in aviation and robotics.
